Key Logic Changes in Existing Code
Attendance.aspx.cs
The Saturday cut logic uses JoinDate and ResignDate from Employees. This does not need to change — because when an employee upgrades, you update Employees.JoinDate to the new engagement start. So the attendance window is automatically correct per engagement period.
However, for wage calculation you'll need to be aware: if an employee was Skilled for part of the month and Unskilled for another part, you'll need to split the wage calculation. This is an edge case — confirm with your business rules whether category changes are effective from the start of the next month (simpler) or mid-month (complex).
Calculation.aspx.cs
Currently it reads Employees.Category to determine wage rate. This is still fine as long as Employees.Category always reflects the current category (which it will, since you update it on upgrade/downgrade).
DBHelper.cs
Add these new query methods:
csharp// Get full history for one employee
GetEmployeeEngagements(string empId)

// Get all employees under a contract
GetEmployeesByContract(int contractId)

// Get active contract for a given category
GetActiveContractByCategory(string category)

// Close an engagement and start a new one (transaction)
TransferEmployeeToNewCategory(string empId, string newCategory, DateTime effectiveDate)

// Get vendor summary stats
GetVendorStats(int vendorId)

Oracle Compatibility Note
Since you're moving to Oracle later, keep these in mind now so migration is easier:
MySQLOracle equivalentAUTO_INCREMENTGENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITYBOOLEANNUMBER(1) with 0/1TEXTCLOB or VARCHAR2(4000)IF NOT EXISTS in CREATENot supported; wrap in exception blocksBacktick identifiersUse double quotes
Your DBHelper.cs already abstracts queries well — when migrating, you'll mainly change the connection string and swap MySqlConnection for OracleConnection. Keeping all SQL in DBHelper.cs (not scattered in page code-behind) will make this migration much less painful.

